The '''Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986''' was a law of the [[War on Drugs]] passed by the [[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]]. Among other things, they changed the system of [[federal supervised release]] from a rehabilitative system into a punitive system. The 1986 Act also prohibited [[controlled substance analog]]s. The bill enacted new [[Mandatory sentencing|mandatory minimum sentences]] for drugs, including [[marijuana]].<ref name=pbssnitch>[https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/snitch/primer/ Snitch: Drug Laws and Snitching&nbsp;– a Primer]. [[Frontline (U.S. TV series)]]. [[Public Broadcasting Service]]. The article also has a chart of mandatory minimum sentences for first time drug offenders.</ref><ref name=frontlinedrugwars>[https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/drugs/cron/ Thirty Years of America's Drug War]. [[Frontline (U.S. TV series)]].</ref>

== History ==

The appearance of [[crack cocaine]], the June 19, 1986 death of [[Len Bias]] (University of Maryland basketball star), the morning after he signed with the NBA champion Boston Celtics, and the June 27, 1986 death of [[Don Rogers (safety)]] (Cleveland Browns, 1985 Defensive Rookie of the Year) -- both from cocaine use,{{sfn|Easley|2011}} encouraged U.S. Rep. Thomas P. (Tip) O'Neill, Jr. (D-MA), the Speaker of the House of Representatives, to mobilize the House Democratic leadership to assemble an omnibus anti-drug bill that became the Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986. <ref name="PBS Frontline Snitch">[https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/snitch/procon/sterling.html]</ref> The congressional interest and intense news coverage created a [[moral panic]] surrounding [[cocaine]] use, which had earlier been viewed in a more benign or even positive way.{{sfn|Musto|2005|p=11}} that made enacting this legislation so important. <ref> Reinarman and Levine, "Crack in America: Demon Drugs and Social Justice", Univ. of Cal. Press, 1997 </ref> In September and October of 1986, the House (with a Democratic majority) and the Senate (with a Republican majority) competed over which could propose the most severe laws in advance of the pivotal midterm election.{{sfn|Musto|2005|p=12}}

A few House [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]] expressed considerable concern about the provisions of the bill. However, most ultimately voted for it, describing election pressures and fear of criticism as swaying their decision. Representative [[Mike Lowry]] (D), who voted against the bill, described the process as "legislation by political panic". Representative [[Charles Schumer]] (D), who voted in favor of the bill, said "the policies are aimed at looking good rather than solving the problem." The House passed the Senate version with a 378–16 majority on October 17, 1986.{{sfn|Murakawa|2014|p=133}}

== Contents ==

=== Money Laundering Control Act ===
The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986 was enacted as Title I of the Anti-Drug Abuse Act.{{sfn|Richards|1998|p=136}}{{sfn|Pollard|Daly|2014|p=16.19}} This title [[criminalization|criminalized]] [[money laundering]] for the first time in the United States.{{sfn|Pollard|Daly|2014|p=16.19}} It also amended the [[Bank Secrecy Act]], the [[Change in Bank Control Act]], and the [[Right to Financial Privacy Act]]{{sfn|Pollard|Daly|2014|p=16.19}}
<!-- There is substantially more literature on the Money Laundering Control Act of 1986 -->

=== Drug crimes ===

Along with the [[Comprehensive Crime Control Act of 1984]], the act substantially increased the number of drug offenses with mandatory minimum sentences.{{sfn|Reamer|2005|p=134}}

This act mandated a minimum sentence of 5 years without parole for possession of 5 grams of crack cocaine while it mandated the same for possession of 500 grams of powder cocaine. This 100:1 disparity was reduced to 18:1, when crack was increased to 28 grams (1 ounce) by the [[Fair Sentencing Act]] of 2010.{{cn|date=January 2018}}

=== Spending ===

The act [[Authorization bill#Authorization-appropriation process|authorized]] billions of dollars of spending, although substantially less was actually [[Appropriations bill (United States)|appropriated]]. Some of this was used to increase the substance abuse treatment federal [[block grant]] program,{{sfn|Landsberg|2004|p=213}} although treatment providers were disappointed at the reduced appropriations following politicians' earlier promises and authorization.{{sfn|Musto|2005|p=12}}

Other programs funded by the act included drug counseling and education programs,{{sfn|Pollard|Daly|2014|p=16.19}} [[AIDS research]],{{sfn|Landsberg|2004|p=213}} and international cooperation to limit drug production.{{sfn|Pollard|Daly|2014|p=16.19}}

The Act also included the ''Drug Free Schools and Communities Act'', which required colleges to establish drug abuse education and prevention programs.{{sfn|Dowdall|2013|p=128}}

== Impact ==

The law led to an increase in average time imprisoned for drug crimes from 22 months to 33 months.{{sfn|Shewan|2013|p=89f}}

