{{Refimprove|date=December 2010}} {{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}} {{Infobox treaty | name = Treaty of Ancon | long_name = Treaty of Peace between Chile and Peru | image = Treaty of Ancón.svg | image_width = | caption = | type = | date_drafted = | date_signed = {{Start date|1883|10|20|df=y}} | location_signed = Ancón, Peru | date_sealed = | date_effective = | condition_effective = | date_expiration = | negotiators = | signatories = * {{flag|Peru}} * {{flag|Chile}} | depositor = | citations = | languages = Spanish | wikisource = }}
The '''Treaty of Ancón''' was signed by [[Chile]] and [[Peru]] on October 20, 1883, in the [[Ancón District]] near [[Lima]]. It was intended to settle the two nations' remaining territorial differences at the conclusion of their involvement in the [[War of the Pacific]] and to stabilise post-bellum relations between them.
Under the treaty's terms, Chile gained control over [[Tarapacá Province (Peru)|Tarapacá]]. Chile was also to retain the conquered provinces of [[Tacna Region|Tacna]] and [[Arica Province|Arica]] for ten years, after which their fate was to be decided by a plebiscite. The plebiscite was never held.<ref>Egaña, Rafael (1900) ''The Tacna and Arica question. Historical antecedents.--Diplomatic action. Present state of the affair'' (translated from the Spanish edition by Edwin C. Reed) Barcelona Printing Office, Santiago, Chile, {{OCLC|19301902}}</ref>
Finally, in 1929, through the mediation of the [[United States]] under [[President of the United States|President]] [[Herbert Hoover]], an accord was reached. Under the [[Tacna-Arica compromise]], Chile kept Arica, while Peru regained Tacna and received [[USD]] $6 million indemnity and other concessions.<ref>Jane, Lionel Cecil (1930) "The question of Tacna-Arica ..." ''Transactions of the Grotius Society'' 15: pp.&nbsp;93–119</ref>
Another important provision in the treaty said that Chile could not cede sovereignty of former Peruvian territories to other nations without asking Peru first. The Chapter has been invoked once, during the [[Atacama border dispute#Chilean proposal of 1975|Chilean proposal of 1975]] that offered Bolivia sovereignty over some minor ports. The Peruvian government rejected the proposed land swap.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Abrazo de Charaña: Chile y Bolivia restablecen relaciones diplomáticas, después de trece años |publisher=Diario La Tercera |language=es |url=http://siglo20.tercera.cl/1970-79/1975/notas1.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080323115336/http://siglo20.tercera.cl/1970-79/1975/notas1.htm |archivedate=23 March 2008 |deadurl=yes |df=dmy }}</ref>
